	abstract = {As a transient X-ray binary, MAXI J1659-152 contains a black hole candidate as its compact star. MAXI J1659-152 was discovered on 2010 September 25 during its only known outburst. Previously-published studies of this outburst indicate that MAXI J1659-152 may have an extreme retrograde spin, which, if confirmed, would provide an important clue as to the origin of black hole spin. In this paper, utilizing updated dynamical binary-system parameters (i.e. the black hole mass, the orbital inclination and the source distance) provided by {\textbackslash}cite\{Torres2021\}, we analyze 65 spectra of MAXI J1659-152 from {\textbackslash}emph\{RXTE\}/PCA, in order to assess the spin parameter. With a final selection of 9 spectra matching our \$f\_\{{\textbackslash}mathrm\{sc\}\} {\textbackslash}lesssim 25 {\textbackslash}\%\$, soft-state criteria, we apply a relativistic thin disk spectroscopic model {\textbackslash}texttt\{kerrbb2\} over 3.0-45.0 keV. We find that inclination angle correlates inversely with spin, and, considering the possible values for inclination angle, we constrain spin to be \$-1 {\textless} a\_\{*\} {\textbackslash}lesssim 0.44\$ at 90{\textbackslash}\% confidence interval via X-ray continuum-fitting. We can only rule out an extreme prograde (positive) spin. We confirm that an extreme retrograde solution is possible and is not ruled out by considering accretion torques given the young age of the system.},
